04743nam a22006015i 9780226250588DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20172017ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2016035743  a9780226250588  a(DE-B1597)550270  a(OCoLC)980875148  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aLA226b.L32 2017 4aLA226b.L32 2019 7aEDU0000002bisacsh04a378.732231 aLabaree, David F., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Perfect Mess :bThe Unlikely Ascendancy of American Higher Education /cDavid F. Labaree. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- t1 A System without a Plan -- t2 Unpromising Roots -- t3 Adding the Pinnacle and Keeping the Base -- t4 Mutual Subversion -- t5 Balancing Access and Advantage -- t6 Private Advantage, Public Impact -- t7 Learning to Love the Bomb -- t8 Upstairs, Downstairs -- t9 A Perfect Mess -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRead the news about America’s colleges and universities—rising student debt, affirmative action debates, and conflicts between faculty and administrators—and it’s clear that higher education in this country is a total mess. But as David F. Labaree reminds us in this book, it’s always been that way. And that’s exactly why it has become the most successful and sought-after source of learning in the world. Detailing American higher education’s unusual struggle for survival in a free market that never guaranteed its place in society—a fact that seemed to doom it in its early days in the nineteenth century—he tells a lively story of the entrepreneurial spirit that drove American higher education to become the best. And the best it is: today America’s universities and colleges produce the most scholarship, earn the most Nobel prizes, hold the largest endowments, and attract the most esteemed students and scholars from around the world. But this was not an inevitability. Weakly funded by the state, American schools in their early years had to rely on student tuition and alumni donations in order to survive. This gave them tremendous autonomy to seek out sources of financial support and pursue unconventional opportunities to ensure their success. As Labaree shows, by striving as much as possible to meet social needs and fulfill individual ambitions, they developed a broad base of political and financial support that, grounded by large undergraduate programs, allowed for the most cutting-edge research and advanced graduate study ever conducted. As a result, American higher education eventually managed to combine a unique mix of the populist, the practical, and the elite in a single complex system. The answers to today’s problems in higher education are not easy, but as this book shows, they shouldn’t be: no single person or institution can determine higher education’s future. It is something that faculty, administrators, and students—adapting to society’s needs—will determine together, just as they have always done.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEducation, Higher - United States - History - 19th century. 0aEducation, HigherzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aEducation, HigherzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh  aAmerica.  aAutonomy.  aCollege.  aHigher education.  aMarket.  aSystem.  aUniversity.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311071193640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226250588423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/978